167.—23. Quid umquam . . . accederet: v. crit. n. for the ingenious suggestion of Mr. Davies, that these words should be transposed to ἓ 170, where they would refer to the elder Oppianicus. Taking them as they stand, the meaning of the clause cum flle verbum . . . potuerit is far from certain. (1) It should mean ‘ at a time when he could not have opened his mouth in this very case,' being a minor. But Cluent. might have wished to guard against future contingencies. (2) ‘ Since he could not (then or now) utter a sentence in his own cause’: referring to the infantia (in- ability to speak) of Opp. minor, which Cic. derides in ἓ 65, te appello, Oppianice, te, T.
